<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF82FFFEFE56183F8601B046" authority="(Selys, 1850)" baseAuthorityName="Selys" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[463,853,562,589]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ischnura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="21" pageNumber="820" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramburii">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF82FFFEFE56183F87E0B046" bold="true" box="[463,692,562,589]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="820">Ischnura ramburii</emphasis>
(Selys, 1850)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF82FFFEFF5918658754B15A" blockId="21.[160,1156,616,849]" pageId="21" pageNumber="820">
Not uncommon around ponds and quiet pools along ghuts on St. Thomas: Mahogany Run ghut and ponds, Turpentine Run ghut, and Donoe Road ghut. There is one early record from St. John (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF82FFFEFE0B18A0870CB0CD" author="Whitehouse FC" box="[402,600,685,710]" pageId="21" pageNumber="820" pagination="199 - 202" refId="ref31729" refString="Whitehouse FC. 1939. Notes on some tropical dragonflies. Can Entomol. 71 (9): 199 - 202. doi: 10.4039 / Ent 71199 - 9." type="journal article" year="1939">Whitehouse 1939</bibRefCitation>
). Adults are blue to green, but immature females are red with the abdomen black above and blue ventrally. It is broadly distributed in 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF82FFFEFF3918FF8474B100" box="[160,288,754,779]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="21" pageNumber="820">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF82FFFEFEB418FF8757B100" author="Ramirez A &amp; Maldonado-Benitez N &amp; Mariani-Rios A &amp; Figueroa-Santiago J" box="[301,515,754,779]" pageId="21" pageNumber="820" pagination="9711" refId="ref28863" refString="Ramirez A, Maldonado-Benitez N, Mariani-Rios A, Figueroa-Santiago J. 2020. Dragonflies and damselflies (Odonata) from Puerto Rico: a checklist with notes on distribution and habitat. PeerJ. 8: e 9711. doi: 10.7717 / peerj. 9711." type="journal article" year="2020">Ram√≠rez et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
) and listed in the grey literature by 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF82FFFEFC0F18FF810AB100" author="Platenberg RJ" box="[918,1118,754,779]" pageId="21" pageNumber="820" refId="ref28514" refString="Platenberg RJ. 2006. Wetlands conservation plan for St. Thomas and St. John, US Virgin Islands. St. Thomas (U. S. Virgin Islands): Division of Fish and Wildlife; p. 101." type="journal volume" year="2006">Platenberg (2006)</bibRefCitation>
for either St. Thomas or St. John without specific location. This is, therefore, the first confirmed record from St. Thomas.
</paragraph>
